<div id="review_476593270" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/476593270" />
    <a title="Shea Mastison" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2796168-shea-mastison"><img alt="Shea Mastison" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1334891459p2/2796168.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/476593270?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shea Mastison" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shea Mastison" href="/user/show/2796168-shea-mastison">Shea Mastison</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer476593270" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8865354341211150098">&quot;The motor force of progress is truth and not lies.&quot; Trotsky is an interesting political figure from the 20th century. He was the &apos;Left Opposition&apos; to Stalin; and a political scapegoat for nearly every catastrophe that befell the Soviet Union after Lenin&apos;s death. In this book, Trotsky uses wit and cold facts to dismantle the bureaucratic mess that was the U.S.S.R. <br/><br/>It&apos;s not that Trotsky disagrees with the objectives; he&apos;s just highly skeptical of the &quot;new aristocracy&quot; that had built itself upon t</span>
  <span id="freeText8865354341211150098" style="display:none">"The motor force of progress is truth and not lies." Trotsky is an interesting political figure from the 20th century. He was the 'Left Opposition' to Stalin; and a political scapegoat for nearly every catastrophe that befell the Soviet Union after Lenin's death. In this book, Trotsky uses wit and cold facts to dismantle the bureaucratic mess that was the U.S.S.R. <br /><br />It's not that Trotsky disagrees with the objectives; he's just highly skeptical of the "new aristocracy" that had built itself upon the dictatorship of the proletariat. It seems that Marxists of various stripes are awfully good at criticism; but their solutions are fantastically unimpressive. <br /><br />Read this if you are a political junkie. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8865354341211150098" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


