    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2877250763" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2877250763" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4424141-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1296524957p2/4424141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2877250763?book_show_action=true">Jun 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/4424141-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2877250763" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17997202348147889825">Reading The Revolution Betrayed along with What Is to Be Done feels like reading tragedy. If What Is to Be Done is the Agamemnon, The Libation Bearers the October Revolution, then The Revolution Betrayed is the Eumenides and Trotsky is Orestes, trying to find reason among the blood that was shed for Marxism and seeking justice before the Furies in the Comintern rip him to shreds. <br/><br/>The Revolution Betrayed unflinchingly investigates how the tactics of Lenin that overthrew the despot king led to civ</span>
  <span id="freeText17997202348147889825" style="display:none">Reading The Revolution Betrayed along with What Is to Be Done feels like reading tragedy. If What Is to Be Done is the Agamemnon, The Libation Bearers the October Revolution, then The Revolution Betrayed is the Eumenides and Trotsky is Orestes, trying to find reason among the blood that was shed for Marxism and seeking justice before the Furies in the Comintern rip him to shreds. <br /><br />The Revolution Betrayed unflinchingly investigates how the tactics of Lenin that overthrew the despot king led to civil war, led to compromises with capitalism among the NEP men, Kulaks and peasant farmers and resulted in a totalitarian bureaucracy, complete with show trials and class liquidation. <br /><br />Like Orestes in the Temple of Athena, Trotsky tries to make sense of it all. As The Revolution Betrayed opens, Lenin’s prescriptions of a vanguard party willing to form a series of transactional alliances with bourgeois forces to overleap history and achieve a Social Democratic revolution in Russia has devolved into a Thermidorian reaction against the experimental freedom of the 1917 revolution. Trotsky, Lenin’s ally and a hero of the revolution, dissects what led to the Stalinist reaction and the replacement of revolutionary regime with a bureaucratic dictatorship. <br /><br />In chapter after chapter, Trotsky lays out the political and economic history of Russia from 1917 to 1936. He describes the triumphs of socialism in the years immediately following 1917 as the book details how a backward, agrarian autocracy emerged from a bloody civil war and came to compete economically, socially and politically with the most powerful economies in the world through an application of Marxist doctrine. Trotsky repeatedly shows how the economic, social and political experimentalism in the immediate aftermath of the revolution led to economic and political advances in the daily lives of workers and peasants. Even when those achievements fall short of their counterparts in the industrialized capitalist countries of Europe, Trotsky points out how these advances came more rapidly and in more inhospitable environments than among any of their European counterparts. <br /><br />How then, he asks, did it all fall apart? In his answer, Trotsky recounts how the hopes of a European wide revolution gave way to a war-time economy as the young Soviet government fought the Whites and their capitalist allies. With the war won, Lenin’s introduction of the NEP ushered in a controlled capitalism while the young socialist experiment in agriculture and industry gained its footing. But with the end of the NEP era, the Soviet state instituted a totalitarian bureaucracy with a new class of rulers in place of the bourgeoisie who instituted piecework, banned workers organizations and liquidated peasant classes. What had been the hoped for economic and political liberation of the mass of Russian workers through the abolition of property, dissolved into the same autocratic rule that the Bolsheviks had set out to replace. <br /><br />Justifying the achievements of the revolution while coming to grips with Stalin’s conservative retrenchment and consolidation of power Trotsky seeks to tell the story of the Soviet Union’s fall from fledgling socialist state, the weak link in the capitalist chain that was going to break the bonds of working people throughout Europe and the world, to an entrenched bureaucracy that has broken faith with the revolution. For anyone interested in the tragedy of the first socialist state, in political history or modern Europe, The Revolution Betrayed is an excellent, well written history that falls outside of western conventional wisdom regarding Russia and the revolution. And is therefore a book well worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17997202348147889825" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

